---

### Key Trade-offs

| Decision | Chosen | Alternative | Why |
|---|---|---|---|
| Vector store | Qdrant | Weaviate / Pinecone | Kubernetes-native StatefulSet, no SaaS dependency |
| BM25 | Elasticsearch | Typesense / Manticore | Team familiarity, better k8s operators |
| Chunking | AST-aware (per function/class) | Fixed-size sliding window | Better semantic boundaries for code; fewer hallucinated context mixes |
| Reranker | cross-encoder (local) | Cohere Rerank API | No egress cost, fits on CPU |
| Agent framework | LangGraph | LlamaIndex Agents | Native graph control flow, HITL gates, easier cycle handling |
| Embedding model | BAAI/bge-base-en-v1.5 | OpenAI text-embedding-3-small | Free, self-hosted, good code retrieval quality |

---

### Capacity Sketch

With ~500k LOC and 512-token chunks, expect roughly 1M chunks. At 768-dim float32 that's ~3 GB of raw vectors — fits comfortably in a single Qdrant instance with 8 GB RAM. Embedding throughput on a 4-core pod with bge-base is ~200 chunks/sec, so a full re-index of 1M chunks takes ~85 minutes — acceptable for hourly CronJob. Delta indexing via webhook gets new commits indexed in under 60 seconds.

---

### Operational Concerns

**Staleness:** webhook-driven delta index keeps Qdrant current within ~30s of a push. The hourly CronJob catches anything the webhook missed (e.g., bulk imports, branch force-pushes).

**Security:** GitHub webhook signature verification (HMAC-SHA256) is in the Git Watcher. Qdrant and Elasticsearch are internal-only (no external Service). LLM API key is a Kubernetes Secret, not an env literal.

**Rollback:** Qdrant PVC is backed up nightly via a Velero snapshot. Collection aliases allow zero-downtime re-index: build a new collection, flip the alias, drop the old one.

**Go gap note:** The Git Watcher is in Kotlin here — if you want to close the Go gap for your job search, that's a clean swap (net/http + gorilla/mux webhook handler, same HMAC-SHA256 logic).
